"Post the Indian Wells, Nadal was to skip the 2022 Miami Masters and make his Clay debut at the 2022 Monte-Carlo Masters but the fracture forced him to skip the event in Monaco where he is a record 11-time champion. With a massive doubt over his participation in Clay events this season, it looked unlikely that Nadal will be fully ready before the 2022 French Open where he is chasing his 14th French Open title and 22nd major. [...] However, good news has certainly presented itself. Nadal hit the clay courts recently for his first practice session as he eyes an return to the Tour quickly. While he will miss this weekâ€™s events as well, the Serbian Open in Belgrade and the Barcelona Open where he is the defending champion, Nadal can look at it as another 2 weeks of practice before he can return to action in May as he had initially planned to play only in Monte-Carlo and Barcelona before the injury ruined his plans." https://firstsportz.com/tennis-news-what-an-illusion-rafael-nadal-ecstatic-after-having-his-first-practice-session-on-clay/

Nadal is the King of Clay. He is going into the French Open with great momentum. If he remains injury free, he should be able to win again. Tennis players who are also great on clay courts are Djokovic, Tsisipas and Thiem. None have a momentum going into the French Open at this point in time.
Fine-tuning

Nadal has won 13/20 French Opens and in the last 10 years alone has won 7 of them. He is the sportsbook favourite as well. This season he's also very hot (17 match winning streak -- this does matter in sports in my view). So it seems the odds are in his favour to win again. Risk will be Djokovic -- who does have a winning record over Nadal in their career head-to-heads, has won the French Open twice (including last year) and is potentially looking for redemption after the Australian Open fiasco.

Nadal has won 13 of the last 17 French Open titles, although he would be the oldest champion ever if he wins this year [1]. Nadal also recently won the Australian Open. He is currently ranked fourth in the world, although Djokovic is currently ranked 2nd and won the French Open last year [2]. Still, barring injury or other reason for withdrawal, Nadal seems to have a good shot at the title.

Looking at Nadals history about 2/3rds of his wins have been at the French Open so there is something about it that suits him. Also heâ€™s been playing well recently and winning tournaments, so heâ€™s still on form.

The crowd looks about right to me. On paper Nadal would be the clear favourite; he's won at Roland Garros 13 times, only losing three times since 2005. He won the Australian open recently after an epic 5-sets against Medvedev, against the odds and after a break due to injury, and covid. And then won again in Mexico. It seems the top players can benefit from a short forced break. So the case against him is whether he can maintain that winning streak at this late stage of his career, and whether Djokovic, Tsitsipas, Medvedev or someone else could create an upset. Perhaps Djokovic could some into form after missing Melbourne entirely and going out in the 4th at Dubai.

If Nadal's feet hold up I think he is pretty clear favourite out of the field. Nadal has been undefeated to start the year after coming back from a foot injury that held him out of competition for the last half of 2021. He will also be on Clay, his favourite surface and one that should be more forgiving on his feet than Hard. (He also has withdrawn from the Miami Open to give him more to recover in preparation for the French open, hopefully preserving the health of his feet).

We are in relatively unknown territory with this question in terms of statistical points of reference, no other athlete is close to Nadal on the clay format at the French Open in wins and streaks of wins as well as age while doing so. However, using Borg's win tally we can take an outside view of the next best for all-time wins there. Borg collected 6 titles between '74 and '81 between the ages of 18-25. Another outside view is looking at all-time grand slam tourney winners (like the French Open) over 35 is very, very low (4).
This is Nadal's happy hunting ground so he must be the favorite so long as his body holds up.
